TY  - JOUR
AU  - Lagerlöf, Nils-Petter
T1  - Slavery and Other Property Rights1
PY  - 2009
Y1  - 2009/01/01
DO  - 10.1111/j.1467-937X.2008.00511.x
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 76
IS  - 1
SP  - 319
EP  - 342
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - The institution of slavery is found mostly at intermediate stages of agricultural development and less often among hunter-gatherers and advanced agrarian societies. We explain this pattern in a growth model with land and labour as inputs in production and an endogenously determined property rights institution. The economy endogenously transits from an egalitarian state with equal property rights to a despotic slave society where the elite own both people and land; thereafter, it endogenously transits into a free labour society, where the elite own the land but people are free.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1467-937X.2008.00511.x
ER  - 



